    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-02-06T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-02-06T14:00:00-05:00" n="755"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d755">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/123: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-06T21:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 6, 1942—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 7—8:59 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>35. My 11, January 16. Lebanese Minister of External Affairs would be grateful if
                    the Department could express an opinion as to the practicability of his
                    proposal.</p>
                <p>In this connection the President of Syria has just sent a verbal message to me to
                    the effect that the Syrian Government was prepared to make any provisional
                    arrangement we wished to safeguard all American interests until after the war.
                    He states German propaganda is spreading reports that the only reason the United
                    States refuses to recognize Syrian independence is that we are preparing a
                    scheme for the extension of Jewish influence in these territories and therefore
                    do not wish to tie our hands. Also because we have no confidence whatever in the
                    stability of the Levant States.</p>
                <p>Repeated to London. By mail to Cairo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
